\begin_layout Section
\noindent
Content
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each day of the workshop will contain three two-hour sessions of instruction.
 The sessions will be interactive, allowing students to learn by doing.
 Typically, the instruction sessions will be structured as 20 minute lecture
 segments, interleaved with 10-20 minute problem solving sessions.
 During these sessions, students will work on solving a narrowly defined
 programming problem, using the library or tool that is being presented
 during that segment.
 For example, an incomplete code segment will be provided and students will
 be asked to write the remaining code, to complete the exercise.
 This form of instruction requires a high level of student engagement.
 The high instructor-to-student ratio will allow instructors to help individual
 students in solving these problem sets during these segments.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the following, we will briefly describe the contents of each of the sessions
 in the above time-table.
 In addition to these formal sessions, we will hold several informal 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

break-out
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 sessions, in which instructors and students can present a topic of interest
 or a software tool in addition to those presented in the more formal instructio
n sessions.
 Topics for these sessions include: software deployment strategies, software
 testing, and stimulus generation and presentation for perceptual exepriments.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\noindent
Introduction to neuroinformatics and reproducible research 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This session will serve as an introduction to the course.
 We will present the the field of neuroinformatics and survey the state
 of the field.
 We will emphasize the principles of reproducible research, as an integral
 part of the goals of neuroinformatics.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\noindent
Scientific computing with Python
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We discuss the packages that extend Python for numerical computing, beyond
 what is part of the language.
 We present the use of the IPython environment for an efficient workflow
 (including debugging, profiling and access to help), and explore the use
 of Numpy arrays, their connection to other data structures in the language
 (lists, dicts and sets), their numerical capabilities, slicing and indexing,
 masking and the notion of structured arrays.
 We conclude with a brief overview of SciPy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\noindent
Version control and literate programming 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will give a very short overview of the central role of version control
 in disciplined programming.
 We'll introduce the basic concepts of distributed version control and start
 exercises putting files into version control, changing them and committing
 them.
 We'll demonstrate merging between repositories as the standard mechanism
 of data and code sharing.
 Next we introduce the idea of literate programming and show examples of
 self-documenting scripts from nitime and other libraries using simple 
\family typewriter
sphinx
\family default
 markup, and more complex lab-notebook style documentation using 
\family typewriter
pweave
\family default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\noindent
Neuroimaging data formats
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We start by introducing the common data formats, with an emphasis on NIfTI
 and DICOM.
 We introduce the 
\family typewriter
nibabel
\family default
 and 
\family typewriter
pydicom
\family default
 toolboxes.
 Our first example will show creation, saving and loading of a NIfTI file
 using 
\family typewriter
nibabel
\family default
.
 We discuss the structure of NIfTI files and show editing NIfTI metadata
 using 
\family typewriter
nibabel
\family default
.
 We discuss the problems of reading the standard DICOM format and have an
 exercise reading DICOMs using 
\family typewriter
pydicom
\family default
.
 We show conversion of DICOM files to NIfTI files, and practice tuning and
 fixing this conversion using 
\family typewriter
nibabel
\family default
 and 
\family typewriter
pydicom
\family default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\noindent
Image processing 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An overview of existing image processing packages, such as 
\family typewriter
scikits.image, mahotas
\family default
 and 
\family typewriter
simplecv
\family default
 is given.
 We then focus on the built-in tools in the 
\family typewriter
scipy.ndimage 
\family default
package, which include image filtering, geometrical warping, morphology
 and object labelling.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\noindent
Statistics 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This session will introduce the general linear model for modelling of functional
 and anatomical data.
 After fitting the model, we discuss various approaches to multiple comparisons:
 nonparametric methods based on permutation tests; False Discovery Rate
 control and Random Field Theory.
 Exercises will illustrate the theoretical ideas using scikits.statsmodels
 and nipy.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\noindent
Pipelines and data-bases
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first part of the session will present building and executing workflows
 for preprocessing of functional data.
 The second part of the session will present the benefits of storing data
 in neuroimaging databases (e.g.
 XNAT) and will demonstrate retrieving, analyzing and storing results in
 such a database.
 The session will focus on using 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathtt{nipype}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathtt{pyxnat}$
\end_inset

 software libraries.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\noindent
Machine learning
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This session introduces attendees to machine-learning techniques used in
 neuroimaging.
 First we present inverse inference: using the PyMVPA toolkit we analyse
 the dataset of Haxby et al 2001 using various analyses schemes: from searchligh
t analysis to ROI/full-brain classification while introducing the concepts
 such as cross-validation and feature selection.
 Second we explore more of general machine learning concepts such as unsupervise
d learning and penalization.
 We demonstrate them using the scikit-learn toolkit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\noindent
Visualization 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first part of this session exposes how to visualize neuroimaging data.
 We start by introducy the nipy functions to perform 2D and 3D visualization
 of MRI volumes.
 Then we show how, underlying nipy, the 3D visualizations are created with
 Mayavi.
 Finally, we give an overview of the Mayavi pipeline and use it to new visualiza
tions of various datasets.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

In the second part, we demonstrate how to create a simple Graphical User
 Interface for a Python class using Traits and TraitsGUI.
 Such GUIs are helpful for instance in data entry or parameter control.
 The created GUIs can be integrated in larger application architectures.
 We give a brief overview of how this is done in the Connectome Viewer which
 extends Mayavi using the Envisage plugin architecture.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\noindent
Time-series analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will present some basic time-series concepts (the Fourier transform,
 auto-regressive models, etc.) and algorithms (filtering, MAR estimation,
 power spectral density estimation and coherency estimation).
 We will demonstrate the use of these algorithms in univariate and multivariate
 analysis of fMRI, EEG and MEG data.
 Exercises will be based on the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathtt{nitime}$
\end_inset

 software analysis library.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\noindent
Graph theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will present some graph theoretical tools for analyzing functional networks
 derived from neuroimaging data.
 We will demonstrate the application of these tools in quantifying the network
 properties of the brain (clustering, path length, small-worldness) as well
 as visualization of this complex network data.
 Exercises will be based upon the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathtt{networkx}$
\end_inset

 python library.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\noindent
Diffusion imaging
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We start with a very brief overview of the steps involved in processing
 diffusion MRI data.
 We will present tools available in 
\family typewriter
dipy
\family default
 for diffusion signal reconstruction and modeling, tractography propagation,
 visualization and iteraction.
 We will also show methods of registering tractographies between brains
 and segmentation algorithms.
 If time permits, we will sketch how to create your own tractographic atlas
 and automatically identify bundles of interest.
 Exercises will use 
\family typewriter
dipy
\family default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Student projects: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the final day of the workshop, students will form small groups (2-3 in
 each group) and work on group projects.
 These projects can take on of the following formats: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A contribution to one of the libraries presented during the workshop.
 This can take the form of an enhancement or addition to the libraray, a
 fix to one of the bugs in the bug-tracker of the project, a tutorial on
 the usage of one of the features of the library or an example usage for
 the documetation of the project.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A solution to some data analysis problem of interest to the group.
 This can take the form of a program integrating and combining usage of
 different tools presented during the workshop.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The final instruction session will be devoted to short (12 minute) presentations
 of the projects.
 
\end_layout

