\begin_layout Paragraph*
\noindent
Rationale and goals: This course will teach neuroimaging researchers to
 use modern open-source software development, in order to create tools for
 reproducible research.
 We will focus on best practices in software development, using the programming
 language Python.
 In addition, we will present specific solutions to analysis problems in
 neuroimaging, with an emphasis on problem-solving with real data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
\noindent
Target audience: Neuroimaging researchers at the graduate student or post-doc
 level with a strong interest in learning best practices in the use and
 development of reproducible research tools.
 We seek to increase the opportunities given to groups under-represented
 in neuroinformatics (e.g.
 women and scientists from countries outside the developed world) and encourage
 members of these groups to apply.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
\noindent
Requirements: Programming experience in Python, Matlab or C/C++ and a strong
 interest in learning software development tools is expected.
 In addition, prior experience or theoretical background in neuroimaging
 (fMRI, MRI, EEG, or other techniques) is assumed.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
\noindent
Structure: The first day of the course will focus on basic tools for scientific
 programming (including version control, ipython, numpy, scipy, matplotlib,
 etc.).
 Days 2-4 will each be divided into three two-hour sessions devoted to general
 topics, such as statistics, machine learning, time series analysis, and
 visualization, as well as presenting several neuroimaging-specific Python
 libraries including nipy, dipy, nibabel, nitime, pymvpa, and nipype (see
 http://nipy.org).
 Each session will be interleaved with hands-on problem solving sessions.
 The last day of the course will have the students work in small groups
 (2-3 people) on selected team projects to analyze real data using the tools
 presented.
\end_layout

